# The Dual-Write Problem and the Outbox

Every event-driven system hits this wall:

```csharp
await db.SaveChangesAsync();                    // ✅ order saved
await bus.Publish(new OrderPlaced(order.Id));    // 💥 broker down / process crash
// → order exists, event never sent: inventory never decrements, email never fires
```

Swap the order? Then the event may fire for an order whose transaction **rolls back** — phantom event. There is no way to make two independent systems (DB + broker) atomic with plain calls. This is the **dual-write problem**.

## The outbox: make it one write

```csharp
using var tx = await db.Database.BeginTransactionAsync();
db.Orders.Add(order);
db.OutboxMessages.Add(new OutboxMessage(          // same database, SAME transaction
    Id: Guid.NewGuid(),
    Type: "OrderPlaced",
    Payload: JsonSerializer.Serialize(new OrderPlaced(order.Id)),
    CreatedAt: DateTime.UtcNow));
await db.SaveChangesAsync();
await tx.CommitAsync();          // order + pending event commit atomically — or neither
```

A background **relay** (hosted service) polls unpublished outbox rows → publishes to the broker → marks published. Broker down? Rows wait. Relay crashes after publish, before marking? Message goes out **twice** — and your idempotent consumers (last lesson!) shrug. The guarantee chain: *at-least-once end-to-end, exactly-once effect via consumer idempotency*.

```csharp
// Relay sketch
var batch = await db.OutboxMessages.Where(m => m.PublishedAt == null)
    .OrderBy(m => m.CreatedAt).Take(100).ToListAsync(ct);
foreach (var msg in batch)
{
    await bus.Publish(msg.Type, msg.Payload, ct);
    msg.PublishedAt = DateTime.UtcNow;
}
await db.SaveChangesAsync(ct);
```

## Practical notes

- **MassTransit and NServiceBus ship this built-in** (EF Core outbox) — configure, don't hand-roll, in production
- Polling interval = added latency (100ms-2s typical); alternatives: SQL Server CDC/change tracking feeding the relay
- Clean up published rows (retention job) — the outbox is a queue, not an archive
- The same table doubles as an **inbox** for consumer-side dedup (store processed message ids transactionally)

One mental model: the outbox turns 'DB write + event publish' into 'DB write (with embedded intent) + eventually-executed intent' — shifting the atomicity to where you actually have it: **inside one database transaction**.
